CRS= Coordinate Reference System 3.5.1.3 Proj4

#proj4 string tells the computer where on earth to locate the coordinates
library(sf)
st_crs(Ausoutline)$proj4string
## [1] "+proj=longlat +datum=WGS84 +no_defs"
#A proj4 string is meant to be a compact way of identifying a coordinate reference system

3.5.1.4 EPSG

#set.. ALWAYS USE THIS LAH
Ausoutline <- Ausoutline %>%
  st_set_crs(., 4326)
#NAH TOO COMPLICATED: or more concisely.. only useful if theres no CRS when you load the data 
Ausoutline <- st_read(here("gadm41_AUS.gpkg"),
                      layer='ADM_ADM_0') %>% 
  st_set_crs(4326)

3.5.1.5 Reprojecting your spatial data

AusoutlinePROJECTED <- Ausoutline %>%
  st_transform(.,3112)
#use st_transform to reproject
print(AusoutlinePROJECTED)

  st_as_sf()

###3.5.2

library(raster)
## Loading required package: sp
library(terra)
## terra 1.8.70
jan<-terra::rast(here("wc2.1_5m_tavg_01.tif"))
# have a look at the raster layer jan
jan
## class       : SpatRaster 
## size        : 2160, 4320, 1  (nrow, ncol, nlyr)
## resolution  : 0.08333333, 0.08333333  (x, y)
## extent      : -180, 180, -90, 90  (xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax)
## coord. ref. : lon/lat WGS 84 (EPSG:4326) 
## source      : wc2.1_5m_tavg_01.tif 
## name        : wc2.1_5m_tavg_01 
## min value   :          -46.042 
## max value   :           34.065
plot(jan)

# set the proj 4 to a new object, project it as a Mollweide projection
pr1 <- terra::project(jan,"+proj=moll +lon_0=0 +x_0=0 +y_0=0 +ellps=WGS84 +datum=WGS84 +units=m +no_defs")
## |---------|---------|---------|---------|=========================================                                          
plot(pr1)

#to WGS84
pr1 <- pr1 %>%
  terra::project(.,"+proj=longlat +datum=WGS84 +no_defs +type=crs")
## |---------|---------|---------|---------|=========================================                                          
plot(pr1)
